Marshal is an EDM producer and writer based in Denver, CO USA. Marshal began creating electronic dance music in 2001 using a laptop and an old school MIDI tracker. Over the years Marshal has upgraded his toolset and sharpened his skills and today with the resources of a full studio filled with hardware and soft synths Marshal has created a unique sound and style. Producing tracks in the realm of Electro House/Trance Marshal creates dynamic tracks that are interesting, catchy and really get you moving on the dance floor.

Tracks of his have been placed in several film projects including Papercat Productions short film ‘Ghost Hunter’ and James Seale’s ‘Juncture’ (www.frontrangefilms.com). Various video and audio podcasts have also used music from Marshal as intro, outro and bumper music. Podcasts like ‘Dude Gamer Zone’, ‘Console Nerds’ (available on iTunes) use Marshal’s tracks on a regular basis.

Currently Marshal is working to develop a live setup to perform in front of audiences. Stressing that the performances will feature original music by Marshal and focus on real-time performance (not DJing) Marshal hopes to expand his fan base by taking his sound directly to clubs and bars in the area.

I'll start here, and keep adding as I go. I am currently a student, 23 years old. I study Computer science and engineering. I started Schooling right after high school at the University of Washington - personal issues, however, led me to take a 2-year hiatus, with the intent of returning to the University of Washington. I'm currently staying with and caring for my dad, who has been diagnosed with ALS several months ago, an ultimately fatal disease. I've learned a lot. On my own, I've come to understand that a little bit of confidence can go a long way in pursuit of knowledge, and goals.

When I began my first programming class - the basics - Python, programming, as I viewed it, looked as tedious as it was confusing.I thought that there was no possible way I could ever learn it. Apparently, I was wrong. I'm not going to tell you I'm any sort of master at python, just that I came to the realization that I was capable of learning it. It turns out that not only was I able to understand the material easily, but I became addicted to discovering and learning what I could do with the language. On my own time, I spent hours each day unable to pull away from coding, and I was so dedicated to creating a basic Login System with password recovery and several other banal things that you would expect from a basic system of this kind. It began with a template I found online. Very Basic. The Script was simply a password only system - no confirmation, username, account creation - anything. You would simply type in whatever you like and it would just return some kind of generic term. It served no function, at least not a practical function. Well, I analyzed some basic aspects of it, but I wanted more, and I wanted it to be my own. I wanted a username entry. So I added one, to an already modified version of the template. I instantly ran into issues where the script would ignore every part of the script. it was dysfunctional. After these types of errors occurred I did a cursory search afterword pertaining to instances in which things of this nature would not output correctly. I couldn't just copy code directly, and I didn't want to anyways. So I learned the principles and nature as to HOW that code worked, and how I could implement that knowledge to my own use. My entire venture was a constant "Why isn't this working..." thought process and having to learn new ways to make things work - Rearranging, deleting, etc. Which eventually led to my "Final" "Program" as of the end of that class. I was proud because I was far ahead of the class, which was funny to me. I did other stuff like an install system, creating an .exe file so it could run, irrespective of whether or not python was installed on the user's computer (Py2exe). Figuring out how in the hell I could implement a picture converted into ASCII type art to appear at the end of the script in python without breaking the whole thing was one excruciatingly annoying task at the time. I'm now working on several projects, all of which require me to learn a great deal.

Eventually, I purchased My first printer, an Anet A6 (Prusa i3 Clone) of which I knew nothing about - zero(point)zero. The original intent of the purchase of my old printer was actually to be used for the purposes of rapid prototyping parts for a custom IoT project I was going to work with a roommate on. The aforementioned project never really came to fruition but came to shape my interests in 3D printing and striving to further my knowledge and expertise. When I first started, with my original A6, I was barely able to print Cura's Robot man - it looked like a stringy blob. However, after massive amounts of tuning, patience, calibration, and many laborious hours of time and effort I was able to create hardware and objects with finely detailed logos and lettering. With each update, it became easier and easier to get the print I wanted - faster. I started printing on styrofoam in a 9'x11' dorm room, at the foot of my bed. I've come a long way, and I continue looking forward and striving for greater goals.

My work explores Terrestrial manifestations through combining tactile,
sculptural forms, and audio; creating immersive environments, unNatural History
Dioramas, and performative, wearable structures questioning Human origin and
mythos.
My ‘jewelry’ serves as maquettes and experiments towards my sculptural work.
The majority of my work draws from my fascination with the artistic
representation of natural history, the creation of fictitious places in literature and
my interest in Cordyceps fungus – in particular; Cordyceps unilateralis, a species
of entomopathogenic fungus that infects and alters the behaviour of ants in order
to ensure the widespread distribution of its spores.
The body of work, An unNatural History created for Urban Glass Brooklyn and
featured during SOFA, NY 2009 is an example of this passion to bring the
microcosmos to the macro through metal, glass, mixed/multi-media, often
'wearable' maquettes.
If we can say that the world of science is synonymous with truth and the world of
art with that of fiction, I want to tread a middle ground that is unusual and
seemingly beyond belief, yet also familiar.
